C<pre><code>int sum_array_rows(int a[M][N]) {
    int sum = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; M; i++)
        for (int j = 0; j &lt; N; j++)
            sum += a[i][j];
    return sum;
}
</code></pre> - Locality:    - Spatial: Array accessed in row-major order (stride-1).   - Temporal: Variable <code>sum</code> accessed each iteration. - Answer: ✅ Good locality (both spatial and temporal).

C<pre><code>int sum_array_cols(int a[M][N]) {
    int sum = 0;
    for (int j = 0; j &lt; N; j++)
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; M; i++)
            sum += a[i][j];
    return sum;
}
</code></pre> - Locality:    - Stride-N pattern (non-contiguous memory access).   - Answer: ❌ Poor locality unless <code>M</code> is very small.

C<pre><code>typedef struct {  
    int a;  
    double d;  
} struct_t;  

double fun(int i) {  
    volatile struct_t s;  
    s.d = 3.14;  
    s.a[i] = 1073741824;  // Out-of-bounds access  
    return s.d;  
}  
</code></pre> Results: - <code>fun(0)</code> → <code>3.14</code> ✅ - <code>fun(3)</code> → <code>2.00000061035156</code> ❌ (Corrupted memory).

